'{"corrected_text":"POLITICAL.\\nNathaniel Hawthorne said that one of\\nthe most terrible consequences of the war\\nwould be the contention of the American people with one bullet-headed general,\\nas president, after another, for the next\\nthirty years.\\nHob Toombs, of Georgia, who says\\nwhat he thinks much more boldly than\\nJ. Q. Davis, is to be called before the Congres¬\\nsional Ku-klux\' committee to give his\\ntestimony as to the condition of the south.\\nWe hope Toombs will respond, for he may\\nbe enable to let us know what is his\\nground for the faith that is in him that\\nthe southern people want another war.\\nHe talked war enough to revolutionize the\\nwestern hemisphere to our correspondent\\nrecently, and we are curious to see what\\nhe will say to the congressional committee\\non that head. New-York Herald.\\nLet\'s-hou, Ill., H. Hill\'s presence at the\\ndinner given by Gov. Hullock to senator\\nCanfield and other northern republicans, a\\nfew nights since, at Atlanta, has furnished\\nthe Macon (Ga.) Telegraph a fourth\\nillustrating verification that men change\\nand men change with them, and it says:\\n"Think of the gulf that now intervenes be¬\\ntween them, as a, and that\\npeace and accord so much needed, might\\nnot now be so deep as it had fewer\\nbitter words been spoken on both sides.",""has_modifications":true}'
