'{"corrected_text":"The New Ambassador to France.\\nGen. Horace Porter, the new Am¬\\nbassador to France, is the author of\\nthe most complete and comprehensive history of Grant\'s military\\ncareer now appearing in The Cen¬\\ntury Magazine, under the title of\\n\\"Campaigning with Grant.\\" Wash¬\\nington is very happy in her represent¬\\native at the principal courts of\\nEurope. Gen. Porter, a worthy suc¬\\ncessor of Mr. Whittaw, Resid, is a\\nman of wit, a scholar, a collector and\\na gentleman. It was he who said at\\na Fourth of July celebration, \\"Gen¬\\ntlemen, let us not forget that we\\nwere all Englishmen until we signed\\nthe Declaration of Independence.\\"\\nAnd on another occasion, when the\\nevacuation of Yorktown was men¬\\ntioned in a half apologetic way by a\\nspeaker at a banquet where a com¬\\npany of English gentlemen were\\npresent, I heard him in his pleasant,\\nhumorous way remark, \\"Anybody\\nwho knows Yorktown couldn\'t be\\nsurprised at the English general\\nbeing quite willing to get out.\\"\\nWith a native American\'s love for\\nhis country, Gen. Porter has a hearty\\nadmiration for this other land of\\nliberty which has set the example of\\nfreedom to the whole world. Joseph\\nHailton in Cigarette Papers.",""has_modifications":true}'
